{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518568"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12932"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.05,0.18,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112756"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94790"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1013"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12960"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112756"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a non-productive cough and fever for 2 days. On further questioning, he has also had a six-month history of weight loss, fatigue, itching and early satiety. He has had three chest infections in the last three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his heart rate is 108 beats per minute, blood pressure 100/73 mmHg, oxygen saturation 92% on room air, respiratory rate is 18 per minute, temperature 38\u00b0C. On auscultation of the chest, there is increased tactile and vocal fremitus in the right lower lobe. He also has an enlarged spleen palpable 6 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis investigation results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 90 g/L (135 \u2013 180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite Cell Count: 104.6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyeloblasts: 2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt;0.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyelocyte: 60 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt;0.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMetamyelocyte: 9 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt;1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 19 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.8 \u2013 7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes: 3 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.0 \u2013 3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonocytes: 0.6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0.2 \u2013 0.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils: 5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0.02 \u2013 0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBasophils: 6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt;0.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 115 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150 \u2013 450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 50 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBone marrow examination reveals markedly hypercellular marrow with a myeloid to erythroid ratio of 15:1 with less than 5% of myeloblasts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic myeloid leukaemia","Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia","Acute myeloid leukaemia","Leukemoid reaction","Primary myelofibrosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features of this patient are consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic myeloid leukaemia (CML), \u003C/strong\u003Ea myeloproliferative neoplasm (MPN). Pruritus often occurs in CML, as basophilia results in histamine release and hence causes itching. Massive splenomegaly is contributing to his early satiety. His incompetent neutrophils lead to recurrent infections despite his high white cell count.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main laboratory feature is a marked and left-shifted leucocytosis with all maturation stages seen. This includes myeloblast, however a marked increase (\u0026gt;20%) defines acute myeloid leukaemia. Basophilia and eosinophilia are also commonly seen. The diagnosis is confirmed by identification of BCR::ABL1 fusion gene as a result of translocation between chromosome 9 and 22.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL)\u003C/strong\u003E is an important diagnosis to consider in an older patient with constitutional symptoms, lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and recurrent infections. However, CLL is less likely as this causes a lymphocytosis, not basophilia. Thrombocytopenia also supports a diagnosis of CLL, as immune thrombocytopenic purpura can be associated with CLL. CLL does not explain this patient\u0027s bone marrow findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myeloid leukaemia (AML)\u003C/strong\u003E is another important diagnosis to consider in an older patient with constitutional symptoms and leucocytosis. However, AML typically presents with a more acute onset of symptoms. Peripheral blood smear and bone marrow examination would show a much higher percentage of myeloblast (typically \u0026gt;20%), which is not consistent with this patient\u0027s findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukemoid reaction\u003C/strong\u003E is a reactive process that can mimic leukaemia, often in response to severe infection or inflammation. However, it does not typically present with the chronic symptoms seen in this patient, nor does it usually show the marked basophilia and eosinophilia seen here. While splenomegaly can be seen in infections, a marked splenomegaly as seen in this case would be unusual and suggests a MPN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary myelofibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a MPN in which normal bone marrow is gradually replaced with fibrous scar-like material. Over time, this leads to progressive bone marrow failure. This results in anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and extramedullary haematopoiesis, for example in the spleen and liver, which become enlarged as a result. Bone marrow would show hypercellularity, abnormal megakaryocytes, and fibrosis. Peripheral blood smear would show tear drop cells and leucoerythroblastic film.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical features of chronic myeloid leukaemia are fatigue, weight loss, splenomegaly, and pruritus.","Peripheral blood smear shows a marked and left-shifted leucocytosis with all maturation stages seen. Basophilia and eosinophilia are also commonly seen.","The diagnosis is confirmed by identification of BCR::ABL1 fusion gene as a result of translocation between chromosome 9 and 22."],"references":["Thompson PA, Kantarjian HM, Cortes JE. Diagnosis and Treatment of Chronic Myeloid Leukemia in 2015. Mayo Clin Proc. 2015;90(10):1440-1454. doi:10.1016/j.mayocp.2015.08.010","Cortes J, Pavlovsky C, Sau\u00dfele S. Chronic myeloid leukaemia. Lancet. 2021;398(10314):1914-1926. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(21)01204-6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94790"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94790"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T13:37:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T13:38:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5370"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112756"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1013"},